---

PROGRAM DESCRIPTION:

This program demonstrates asynchronous multithreading using POSIX threads and semaphores.

The program:

* Creates a shared file named QUOTE.txt
* Writes the process ID to the file
* Creates seven threads using pthread_create()
* Uses a semaphore named FLAG to synchronize access to the shared file
* Even numbered threads sleep for 2 seconds and write the Brian Kernighan quote
* Odd numbered threads sleep for 3 seconds and write the Edsger Dijkstra quote
* Each thread writes to the shared file 8 total times
* The main process waits for all threads using pthread_join()
* The semaphore is destroyed before the program exits

---

DESIGN DECISIONS:

* POSIX threads were used to allow seven bots to execute concurrently.
* A semaphore named FLAG was used to ensure only one thread writes to QUOTE.txt at a time.
* Thread IDs are stored in an array and passed individually to each thread.
* QUOTE.txt is opened and closed during each write operation to ensure proper file handling.

---

EXTRA FEATURES:

* Added descriptive comments throughout the source code.
* Displays a friendly completion message after all threads have finished executing.

---

KNOWN DEFICIENCIES OR BUGS:

* No known bugs at this time.
* Thread execution order may vary between runs because thread scheduling is handled by the operating system and execution is asynchronous by design.

---

LESSONS LEARNED:

* Learned how to create and manage POSIX threads.
* Learned how to synchronize threads using semaphores.
* Learned how race conditions can occur when multiple threads access a shared resource.
* Learned how to use a Makefile to compile and manage a project.
* Learned how thread scheduling affects program execution order.

---

NOTES:

The semaphore prevents multiple threads from writing to QUOTE.txt simultaneously, preventing corrupted output.

